\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\sl240\slmult1\qc\rtlch\af1\afs20\lang1024\ab\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1024\hich\f1\fs20\lang1024\b\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024\b {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024\i0\b Abstract}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\sl240\slmult1\qj\li1024\ri1024\lin1024\rin1024\fi0\rtlch\af1\afs20\lang1024\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1024\hich\f1\fs20\lang1024\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024\i0\b0 Sri Lanka Malay has innovated a prominent and productive copula, which sets it apart from other descendents of colloquial Malay varieties. This copula has developed from the verb {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i dhaathang} \'91to come\'92, which is a grammaticalization path not attested in the l
iterature so far. This paper describes the forms and functions of this copula and shows that it cannot be traced to any of the main input languages of Sri Lanka Malay (Trade Malay, Tamil, Sinhala). Comparing the Sri Lanka Malay case to attested grammatical
ization paths, the paper concludes that the grammaticalization of COME to a copula is less surprising when assuming intermediate stages of \'91resultative\'92 and \'91stative\'92. These subpaths are illustrated by a variety of Creole and non-Creole languages. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s10\cf0\sl240\slmult1\sb240\sa60\keepn\rtlch\afs32\lang1024\ab\ltrch\dbch\langfe1024\hich\fs32\lang1024\b\loch\fs32\lang1024\b {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs32\lang1024\i0\b 1  Introduction}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\sl240\slmult1\qj\sb360\rtlch\af1\afs20\lang1024\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1024\hich\f1\fs20\lang1024\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024{\super 2{\*\footnote 2\pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\sl240\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\sb60\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs16\lang1024\i0\b0 I would like to thank Eva van Lier and Benard Comrie for comments on earlier version of this paper. The usual disclaimers apply.}}}
{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024{{\*\updnprop10000}\up13 }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024 Languages with copulas are widely known in Europe and beyond, but languages without a copula are also frequently encountered. If languages without a copula develop one over time, the source is normally either a former locational verb or a deictic (Stasse
n 1997:91). In this paper, I want to highlight yet another source for a copula, namely the participle of the verb COME, which has grammaticalized into a copula in Sri Lanka Malay.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\sl240\slmult1\qj\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi360\rtlch\af1\afs20\lang1024\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1024\hich\f1\fs20\lang1024\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024\i0\b0 I will first give some information on Sri Lanka Malay (Section {\field{\*\fldinst  REF BMsec_introslm \\h }{\fldrslt 2}}{}) and the types of copula sentences we find in that language (Section {\field{\*\fldinst  REF BMsec_slmcopula \\h }{\fldrslt 3}}{}). I will then show that neither other varieties of Malay nor the contact languages Sinhala and Tamil provide models for 
the development of this particular copula in Sri Lanka Malay (Section {\field{\*\fldinst  REF BMsec_contactlgs \\h }{\fldrslt 4}}{}). I then discuss common sources for the grammaticalization of copulas in Section {\field{\*\fldinst  REF BMsec_sources \\h }{\fldrslt 5}}{} and common targets of grammaticalization for the verb COME in Section {\field{\*\fldinst  REF BMsec_targets \\h }{\fldrslt 6}}{}, showing that the particular 
combination COME{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\af\f5\loch\af\f5 \'ae}copula is not attested. However, three subpaths, namely COME{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\af\f5\loch\af\f5 \'ae}resultative, resultative{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\af\f5\loch\af\f5 \'ae}stative and stative{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\af\f5\loch\af\f5 \'ae}copula are attested, which, when chained, can explain the Sri Lanka Malay facts.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s10\cf0\sl240\slmult1\sb240\sa60\keepn\rtlch\afs32\lang1024\ab\ltrch\dbch\langfe1024\hich\fs32\lang1024\b\loch\fs32\lang1024\b {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs32\lang1024\i0\b {\*\bkmkstart BMsec_introslm}2{\*\bkmkend BMsec_introslm}  Sri Lanka Malay}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\sl240\slmult1\qj\sb60\rtlch\af1\afs20\lang1024\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1024\hich\f1\fs20\lang1024\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang1024\i0\b0 Sri Lanka Malay is the language of the descendents of soldiers, exiles, convicts and slaves who were brought to the island by the colonial powers of the Dutch and the British between roughly 1650 and 1850 (Hussainmiya 1990). The grammar of the language has
 changed dramatically ever since (Adelaar 1991, Smith et\~al. 2004, Ansaldo 2008, Nordhoff 2009) and has shed most of its Austronesian origins to align with the Sri Lankan sprachbund (Bakker 2006), although some traces of Malay grammar still remain (Slomans
on 2006). For instance, the language has changed from SVO to SOV and from prepositional to postpositional. The language has developed more than 20 new bound morphemes, mainly for the marking of TAM and case, which is virtually unheard of in other parts of 
the Malay world. Most of the changes the language has undergone since its arrival on the island 350 years ago were triggered by language contact. The copula, however, does not seem to have a clear origin in any contact language or any historical variety of
 Malay.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s10\cf0\sl240\slmult1\sb240\sa60\keepn\rtlch\afs32\lang1024\ab\ltrch\dbch\langfe1024\hich\fs32\lang1024\b\loch\fs32\lang1024\b {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs32\lang1024\i0\b {\*\bkmkstart BMsec_slmcopula}3{\*\bkmkend BMsec_slmcopula}  The copula in Sri Lanka Malay}
